00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:11,560
 And then it's got this stuff.

52
00:03:11,560 --> 00:03:17,280
 Well, let's say we wanted a bunch of pages that had that everything but the body.

53
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:22,800
 So what we basically then do is we take parts of this,

54
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:25,720
 like the repeated parts, and we put it into a template.

55
00:03:25,720 --> 00:03:32,560
 And then we take the part that we're gonna change every time and

56
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:35,720
 we put it into a template that then extends.

57
00:03:35,720 --> 00:03:41,360
 So see this one here has one line that says extends temple-based.html.

58
00:03:41,360 --> 00:03:46,100
 So this one uses everything in here but then adds some stuff, okay?

59
00:03:46,100 --> 00:03:51,880
 So the basic idea is we split this one big template into reusable parts and

60
00:03:51,880 --> 00:03:53,400
 non-reusable parts.

61
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:57,200
 And then we have a bunch of templates that come off of base.

62
00:03:57,200 --> 00:03:59,640
 We call it base, commonly in object-oriented world,

63
00:03:59,640 --> 00:04:02,200
 because it's like the thing that we're basing it on.

64
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:05,200
 So this is the base and then we're gonna build on it.

65
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:07,440
 Base builds something else on top of it.

66
00:04:07,440 --> 00:04:10,520
 So how this works in practice, we have a view here.

